Mount Windows Images in FTK Imager & Autopsy
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Install and configure FTK Imager and Autopsy on Linux
Mount Windows forensic images using FTK Imager
Analyze mounted images and recover artifacts using Autopsy
Navigate file systems within forensic images
Extract and examine digital evidence from Windows disk images
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command-line knowledge
Understanding of file systems and disk structures
Familiarity with digital forensics concepts
Internet connection for tool installation
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated Linux machine. The provided system is bare metal with no pre-installed forensic tools, so you will install all required software during the lab.

Task 1: Install Required Tools
Subtask 1.1: Update System and Install Dependencies
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install -y wget curl unzip default-jre git build-essential
Subtask 1.2: Install FTK Imager (Linux Alternative - ewf-tools)
Since FTK Imager is Windows-only, we'll use ewf-tools and sleuthkit for image mounting:

sudo apt install -y ewf-tools sleuthkit autopsy
Subtask 1.3: Install Autopsy
wget https://github.com/sleuthkit/autopsy/releases/download/autopsy-4.20.0/autopsy-4.20.0.zip
unzip autopsy-4.20.0.zip
sudo mv autopsy-4.20.0 /opt/autopsy
sudo chmod +x /opt/autopsy/bin/autopsy
Subtask 1.4: Create Sample Windows Image
For demonstration purposes, create a sample disk image:

mkdir ~/forensics-lab
cd ~/forensics-lab
dd if=/dev/zero of=windows_sample.dd bs=1M count=100
Task 2: Mount Windows Forensic Image
Subtask 2.1: Examine Image Information
cd ~/forensics-lab
file windows_sample.dd
mmls windows_sample.dd
Subtask 2.2: Mount Image Using Loop Device
sudo mkdir /mnt/forensic-image
sudo losetup /dev/loop0 windows_sample.dd
sudo mount -o ro,loop /dev/loop0 /mnt/forensic-image
Subtask 2.3: Verify Mount Status
mount | grep forensic
ls -la /mnt/forensic-image/
Subtask 2.4: Create Working Directory Structure
mkdir -p ~/forensics-lab/evidence
mkdir -p ~/forensics-lab/reports
mkdir -p ~/forensics-lab/extracted
Task 3: Analyze Image with Autopsy
Subtask 3.1: Start Autopsy Server
cd /opt/autopsy/bin
sudo ./autopsy
Note: Autopsy will start on http://localhost:9999/autopsy

Subtask 3.2: Access Autopsy Web Interface
Open a web browser and navigate to:

http://localhost:9999/autopsy
Subtask 3.3: Create New Case
Click New Case
Enter case details:
Case Name: Windows_Image_Analysis
Description: Lab 1 - Windows Image Mounting
Investigator: Your Name
Click New Case
Subtask 3.4: Add Host and Image
Click Add Host
Enter host information:
Host Name: Target_System
Description: Windows forensic image analysis
Click Add Host
Click Add Image
Select image location: /home/user/forensics-lab/windows_sample.dd
Choose Partition as image type
Click Add Image
Subtask 3.5: Analyze File System
Navigate to File Analysis tab
Browse directory structure
Examine file metadata
Look for deleted files in $OrphanFiles
Task 4: Extract and Examine Artifacts
Subtask 4.1: Search for Registry Files
In Autopsy interface:

Go to Keyword Search
Search for: *.reg
Review results in Registry section
Subtask 4.2: Examine System Files
# Using command line tools
sudo fls -r /dev/loop0 | grep -i "system32"
sudo icat /dev/loop0 [inode_number] > ~/forensics-lab/extracted/system_file.dat
Subtask 4.3: Timeline Analysis
In Autopsy:

Click Timeline tab
Generate timeline for mounted image
Filter by file types: Executable, Document, Image
Export timeline data
Subtask 4.4: Hash Analysis
# Generate MD5 hash of original image
md5sum ~/forensics-lab/windows_sample.dd > ~/forensics-lab/evidence/image_hash.txt

# Verify image integrity
cat ~/forensics-lab/evidence/image_hash.txt
Task 5: Document Findings
Subtask 5.1: Generate Autopsy Report
In Autopsy, go to Case Management
Click Generate Report
Select report format: HTML
Save report to: ~/forensics-lab/reports/
Subtask 5.2: Create Evidence Log
cat > ~/forensics-lab/evidence/evidence_log.txt << EOF
=== FORENSIC EVIDENCE LOG ===
Case: Windows_Image_Analysis
Date: $(date)
Investigator: Lab Student
Image File: windows_sample.dd
Image Hash: $(md5sum ~/forensics-lab/windows_sample.dd | cut -d' ' -f1)
Mount Point: /mnt/forensic-image
Analysis Tool: Autopsy 4.20.0
Status: Analysis Complete
EOF
Task 6: Cleanup and Unmount
Subtask 6.1: Unmount Image
sudo umount /mnt/forensic-image
sudo losetup -d /dev/loop0
Subtask 6.2: Stop Autopsy Service
# Stop Autopsy server (Ctrl+C in terminal where autopsy is running)
pkill -f autopsy
Subtask 6.3: Verify Cleanup
mount | grep forensic
losetup -a
Verification Steps
Check Installation Success
which ewfinfo
which mmls
ls /opt/autopsy/bin/autopsy
Verify Evidence Integrity
ls -la ~/forensics-lab/evidence/
cat ~/forensics-lab/evidence/image_hash.txt
Review Generated Reports
ls -la ~/forensics-lab/reports/
Common Issues and Solutions
Issue: Autopsy fails to start Solution: Check Java installation and port availability

java -version
netstat -tulpn | grep 9999
Issue: Permission denied when mounting Solution: Ensure proper sudo privileges

sudo chmod 755 /mnt/forensic-image
Issue: Image corruption detected Solution: Verify image integrity

md5sum -c ~/forensics-lab/evidence/image_hash.txt
Conclusion
You have successfully completed mounting and analyzing Windows forensic images using open-source tools on Linux. This lab demonstrated essential digital forensics skills including image mounting, artifact extraction, timeline analysis, and evidence documentation. These techniques form the foundation for professional digital forensics investigations, enabling you to preserve evidence integrity while conducting thorough analysis of Windows systems. The combination of command-line tools and Autopsy provides a comprehensive approach to forensic image analysis that is widely used in cybersecurity and digital forensics fields.
